I’m looking forward to playing and experimenting with glass in ways I haven’t yet! Heading to Detroit this week for a  residency at the Henry Ford Museum. Next week is our opening at Habatat  Galleries Detroit (With @ravenskyriver ♥️) 
🫶🏽Our solo/ co-exhibit, “Confluence,” shows our latest work, and we will exhibit alongside Blown Away friends and the 51st Habatat Internat’l Invitat’l …lots going on! Plus the GAS conference, where we will see old friends from near and far. But mostly far! 
::

⭐️!!

🦄 so, I am trying dinosaurs out again after a 10 year break from them. Fun to see how differently they come out now. The super special chalcedony color (which they make here) is PERFECT for these!

The Henry Ford Museum Hot Shop, in Greenfield Village, Dearborn MI. Beautiful glass studio. Mesquite floors! 3 color pots besides the clear. 
“The Glass Shop was constructed in 1930 to demonstrate the art of glass making as practiced in nineteenth century America. It was modeled after the Boston and Sandwich Glass House, located in Cape Cod, Massachusetts. In 2005, the shop was rebuilt, enlarged and updated with modern equipment. Today, our artisans create up to 10,000 pieces of historic and contemporary Studio Glass annually.” 
♥️♥️♥️
It has been an honor to work here! I feel like a princess. A sweaty, sooty, stinky princess! 🦄 
It’s a beautiful shop with good people working hard together. Today was day 4. Last day of residency tomorrow!

We had lots of preparations to do first couple days. Now getting into the nitty gritty. This is a murrini casting, optical discs attached to the pour-side. We puntied the castings to fire polish/ smooth out everything. 
🔥🔥🔥 Many kinks to work out today with the process of these demanding pieces but I think we are ready to jam on a few more tomorrow. 🔥 I am so grateful for the amazing team at the Henry Ford Museum - Greenfield Village Glass Studio, making dreams come true. Very Special Guest visiting assist from a dear friend and everyone’s favorite human,  @nikodimitrijevic . Yes, we had donuts and coffee you just wouldn’t believe! 
🍩 @yellowlightdetroit 
Specimen series, 
These pieces are meant to offer a closer look at the cross sectioning of a process (murrini technique). A pattern is made by mirroring and stacking them. They are magnified and distorted, colorful and  Biological. This is the series I hoped to develop while here. Let’s see what happens tomorrow!

“65 Million Years” 2023
Blown and sculpted chalcedony glass, made at the Henry Ford glass shop this summer. 
…speaking of dinosaurs… I had such a great bday weekend! Thanks for all the well wishes ❤️🩷

This piece is being considered for the Henry Ford Collection this week, fingers crossed! I enjoyed a week-long residency there in Dearborn/ Detroit this summer. In return, they ask for a piece for their collection. Good trade! ❤️

⭐️ neat thing about this piece is it is all one color, “Chelcedony.” They melt it there at the Henry Ford. The chemical recipe of the color melted allows for the multi-colored glass. You can assert some control, maybe, over which colors (ish) by the way you gather or let the piece get cool & reheat.  after working with it for a whole week, I felt like I got to know it a little. Then it was time to go home! Ah, a wonderful tease!

A Woman’s Life on the Edge of the Sea (Four Decades of Poetry)

Author, activist, doula, grandmother, and singer of songs in reverence to the Earth, Irene Skyriver was born on the shores of the Pacific Northwest Coast. Her heritage is of Northwest Coastal Native (Tlingit and Makah) and European blood. At twenty-five years old and penniless, she moved to a small island community with her two, soon-to-be (@ravenskyriver) three, children. She felt at home in this small community, Lopez Island, on the Salish Sea. In her forty-two years on Lopez Island, she has lived a rich life. Skyriver is a song-keeper for the community and helped establish Winter and Summer Solstice traditions and Passage Rites ceremonies. She and her husband live on a homestead without traditional plumbing—a hand pump at the sink brings fresh spring water—the toilet is a composting outhouse, they eat from her large garden, drink the milk from raised goats, and brew cider from the orchard. In A Woman’s Life on the Edge of the Sea, Skyriver delves deep into her family and heritage and into the richness of nature and Mother Earth

♥️Glass sculpture class in action at our home studio, @calderaglass !  We are finally getting to a promise we made to these very generous folks, who donated to our kickstarter project (glass shop build) a few years back. They prepaid and signed up for a sculpture class at an UNBUILT shop, and now here they are! 
♥️Just a few years ago, none of this was here. We had poured just part of the pad in the spring of 2018 and looked at each other… “now what?” Gulp. We needed help. 
♥️Over 350 people chipped in support, labor, materials, and $$ to help make our dream come true. We still can’t believe it. Thanks to all who believe in us, we are so grateful for you!
♥️Our hearts are full to see the shop full of such amazing talent, history, and creativity this week. This is what we envisioned.

Solid glass bricks. I started messing around with this series at Pittsburgh Glass Center @pghglasscenter  during a residency 5 years ago… and now, these are from last summer’s residency at @thehenryford.
still lots to explore here! Fun to make these, because they use a few different techniques.  The discs are made with several thin layers of glass. The murrini was made with colorpots at the Henry ford. Fused murrini, cast, then all of it firepolished on the punty in the gloryhole.  Im not really sure what they “are” yet… but I was thinking they’re like supersized microscope slides, inviting the viewer to inspect (and hopefully enjoy) pattern and symmetry.
